  "prompt": "Why are Hela cells immortal?",
  "response": "HeLa cells are a widely used line of immortal human cervical cancer cells that were derived from Henrietta Lacks in 1951. The immortality of HeLa cells, meaning their ability to divide indefinitely in vitro, can be attributed to several key factors:\n\n1. **Telomerase Activity**: One of the main reasons HeLa cells are immortal is their ability to maintain telomere length through the expression of the enzyme telomerase. In normal somatic cells, telomeres shorten with each cell division, eventually leading to replicative senescence (where the cells stop dividing). HeLa cells express telomerase, which allows them to maintain their telomeres and divide indefinitely.\n\n2. **Cancer Characteristics**: HeLa cells originated from a tumor, which means they exhibit many of the hallmarks of cancer. These include evading growth suppressors, resisting cell death, sustaining proliferative signaling, and enabling replicative immortality. These characteristics are part of what gives HeLa cells their ability to proliferate without the typical regulatory mechanisms that control normal cell division.\n\n3. **Genetic Mutations**: HeLa cells contain numerous genetic mutations and alterations within various signaling pathways that contribute to their uncontrolled growth. These mutations can affect tumor suppressor genes (like p53) and oncogenes, leading to a loss of normal cell cycle control.\n\n4. **Adaptation to Culture Conditions**: HeLa cells have adapted to and thrive in culture conditions that are not typical for normal cells, allowing them to grow and divide more rapidly and effectively in vitro.\n\nDue to these properties, HeLa cells have become remarkably valuable for biomedical research, including studies in cancer, virology, toxicology, and genetics. However, their use has also raised ethical concerns regarding consent and the use of human tissues in research.",
